==English==
=== Etymology ===
Seventeenth-century British variant of ''[[oh my God]]'', likely intended to avoid [[blasphemy]]<ref>[http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-yeg1.htm "Ye gods and little fishes!"] (World Wide Words)</ref><ref>[http://64.233.161.104/search?q=cache:1Vzxh_H1XEcJ:newpaper.asia1.com.sg/news/story/0,4136,93299,00.html "Gosh, we can't leave God alone when we speak"] (The Electric New Paper News)</ref>.

=== Expression ===
'''[[ye]] [[gods]]!'''
# Said when something is [[surprising]] or beyond belief.
#* '''1851''': [[w:Herman Melville|Herman Melville]], ''[[s:Moby-Dick|Moby-Dick]]'' (Chapter 2)
#*: "Would he not far rather lay him down lengthwise along the line of the equator; yea, '''ye gods!''' go down to the fiery pit itself, in order to keep out this frost?"

==== Derived terms ====
* [[egads]]
* [[ye gods and little fishes]]

